                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14460396" author="spullara" created="Sun, 4 Jul 2004 04:52:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The current behavior of a class name is to return the class so:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AnyClass in groovy == AnyClass.class in Java&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So you can either close this as it is not a bug, or you can lobby to have it changed to your expected behavior.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460476" author="bingran" created="Sun, 4 Jul 2004 06:11:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is a Groovy feature that I wish go away in favor of Java semantics. I know it&apos;s the property syntax thing, but one strong argument for the Java way is performance. The Groovy compiler as of now attempts to resolve every single variable as a class name, wasting a lot of CPU cycles. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The dilemma is with the .class &quot;property&quot;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;a.class &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;is interpreted as &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;a.getClass() &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;in Groovy and &quot;a&quot; has to be an object instance. The same syntax in Java means the Class object for class a. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;BTW, this is also a piece of inconsistancy in Java syntax where .something may not always mean a field access. Another example is the .length in eg. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;new Object[]&lt;/p&gt;
{&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;}
&lt;p&gt;.length. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m wondering if we can build special logic in processing the .class suffix, something like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. try resolving &quot;a&quot; as a class; on failure, and optionally, &lt;br/&gt;
2. interpret it as a.getClass()&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I said &quot;optionally&quot;, because we can also simply mandate using getClass() on a class instance.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460485" author="johnstump" created="Wed, 21 Jul 2004 19:41:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The current groovy syntax also creates problems as reported in issue 515. Basically, we can&apos;t have a static property the same name as a java.lang.Class method, because they conflict:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;class A {&lt;br/&gt;
  static methods = &quot;blah&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
}&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;println A.methods&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;this will return a MethodClosure for the getMethods() method on A.class.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I vote we force the user to use &quot;.class&quot; or getClass() instead of just &quot;A&quot;. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a side note, I also don&apos;t like getting a MethodClosure (method reference) when referring to a method name.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460624" author="blackdrag" created="Tue, 11 Jan 2005 12:04:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;fix got in cvs today. Now a fully qualified class name with a .class will be resolved to the class name given before the dot&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
